  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on preventing criminal proceeds from being integrated into legitimate financial systems\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States first introduced formal reporting requirements\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international anti-money laundering standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- United Nations conventions in 1988 and 2000 expanded global legal frameworks\n- European Union implemented progressive anti-money laundering directives\n- Most countries now have comprehensive legal structures addressing money laundering\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approach:\n- Requires financial institutions to implement robust compliance programs\n- Mandates suspicious activity reporting\n- Establishes know-your-customer (KYC) requirements\n- Imposes significant penalties for non-compliance\n\n5. Ongoing Evolution:\n- Continuously adapting to technological changes\n- Increasing focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction monitoring\n\nThe legal framework continues to develop in response to emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
